<dl id="n04181b"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n04" href="#n04181b">N04 (VI.B.25)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n04all.htm#n04181b"> 181(b)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> deacon <small>color t.b.a.</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n04181b"><li>FW 605.15 </li><li><a href="../../flex/tb/lextb.htm#n04181b">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/tb/l39tb.htm#n04181b">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n04181b">MS BL 47488-25</ms> </li><li>JJA 63:038c <a name="t22d" href="../../FF/fdra/tda.htm#t22d">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/t/t22d.htm#n04181b">Draft: IV&sect;2.2</a> </li> </ul><mm class="note">Note: Inferred page and unit: the remainder of the notebook is torn out. In the Latin Church the ecclesiastical orders are those of bishops, priests, <mark>deacons</mark>, subdeacons, acolytes, exorcists, lectors [readers], <i>ostiarii</i> or doorkeepers, and all are very ancient. Some canonists add another order, that of the tonsure, but this is generally regarded as a mere introduction to the clerical state. Apart from this, very many theologians, among whom is St. Thomas, do not regard the episcopate as a separate order, but only as the completion and extension of the priesthood, and hence reckon the number of the orders as seven. </mm> </dd></dl>
